'''Carbotanium''' is a patented composite material invented by '''Modena Design''', the [[Carbon fibre|carbon composite]] manufacturing and consultancy arm of the Italian car company [[Pagani (automobile)|Pagani]]. It is a combination of [[Titanium|beta titanium]] [[alloy]] with advanced carbon composites, having a matched [[yield strength]] and [[Elastic modulus|moduli of elasticity]] ratio. When the combination is adhesively bonded both parts will approach maximum yield strength and fail at a similar amount of total strain. The [[titanium]] and carbon composites are combined by first abrading the titanium to be bonded, coating the titanium with [[platinum]], aging the titanium, spraying [[Primer (paint)|primer]] on the coated titanium, applying [[adhesive]] to the primer side of the titanium and then applying the [[carbon]] to the adhesive. This allows the carbon composite to bond securely to the titanium. This [[Composite material|composite]] uses the best properties of each component, the combination having a better set of properties than either part. This material is both strong and light.<ref name=googlepatent>{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/patents/US5733390|title=Carbon-titanium composites|accessdate=7 January 2015}}</ref>

==Usage==
Pagani has applied this weave on their latter extra strong and lightweight supercars, the [[Pagani Zonda R|Zonda R]] and [[Pagani Huayra|Huayra]]. Although not all [[Pagani Zonda|Zondas]] are made from carbotanium, some are formed from carbon fibre. They have also used other variations of metal/composites.

