The '''Felicity effect''' is an effect observed during [[acoustic emission]] in a structure undergoing repeated mechanical loading. It negates the effect of emission silence in the structure that is often observed from the related [[Kaiser effect (material science)|Kaiser effect]] at high loads. A material demonstrating the Felicity effect gives off acoustic emission at a lower load than one previously reached in an increasing load cycle regime.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndt-ed.org/EducationResources/CommunityCollege/Other%20Methods/AE/AE_Theory-Sources.htm |title=AE Sources |publisher=Ndt-ed.org |date= |accessdate=2013-12-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndt.net/ndtaz/content.php?id=471 |title=Felicity Effect |publisher=Ndt.net |accessdate=2014-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3VePAhhi_OsC&lpg=PA424&ots=OUhaQMbexL&dq=felicity%20effect&pg=PA424#v=onepage&q=felicity%20effect&f=false |title=Infrastructure Health in Civil Engineering: Theory and Components - Mohammed M. Ettouney, Sreenivas Alampalli - Google Boeken |publisher=Books.google.be |date=2011-09-27 |accessdate=2013-12-31}}</ref>

