The '''Holbrook Superconductor Project''' is the world's first production [[superconductor|superconducting]] [[Electric power transmission|transmission]] power cable.<ref name="schmidt">{{citation | url = http://www.jicable.org/2007/Actes/Session_A3/JIC07_A34.pdf | title = Development and demonstration of a long length transmission voltage cold dielectric superconducting cable to operate in the Long Island Power Authority grid | author = Frank SCHMIDT | year = 2007 }}</ref> The lines were commissioned in 2008.<ref>{{citation | doi = 10.1016/j.physc.2009.05.089 | title = Status of high temperature superconductor cable and fault current limiter projects at American Superconductor | year = 2009 | last1 = Maguire | first1 = J.F. | last2 = Yuan | first2 = J. | journal = Physica C: Superconductivity | volume = 469 | issue = 15-20 | pages = 874 }}</ref> The suburban [[Long Island]] [[electrical substation]] is fed by a 600 meter long tunnel containing about 99 miles of [[high-temperature superconductors|high-temperature superconductor wire]] manufactured by [[American Superconductor]], installed underground and chilled to superconducting temperature with [[liquid nitrogen]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Gelsi | first = Steve | coauthors = | title = Power firms grasp new tech for aging grid | work = | pages = | language = | publisher = Market Watch | date = 2008-07-10 | url = http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/power-firms-grasp-new-technology/story.aspx?guid={3BB486EE-6B51-4B5D-9E91-0099ED4ED291}&dist=msr_1 | accessdate = 2008-07-11}}</ref>
The superconductor is [[bismuth strontium calcium copper oxide]] (BSCCO) which superconducts at liquid nitrogen temperatures. Other parts of the system include a {{convert|13000|gal|liter}} liquid nitrogen storage tank, a [[Brayton cycle|Brayton]] Helium [[Refrigeration|refrigerator]], and a number of [[cryostat]]s which manage the transition between cryogenic and ambient temperatures.<ref name="schmidt"/>
The project was funded by the [[United States Department of Energy]], and operates as part of the [[Long Island Power Authority]] power grid.<ref name="schmidt"/>
