The ''' U-1''' was a 1950s [[liquid hydrogen trailer]] designed to carry [[cryogenic]] [[liquid hydrogen]] (LH<sub>2</sub>) on roads being [[Towing|pulled]] by a powered vehicle. It was designed in response to requirements of the secret US government program code-named ''[[Lockheed CL-400 Suntan|Suntan]]'', which aimed to develop a high speed, high altitude hydrogen-powered military aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sloop|first1=John L|title=Liquid hydrogen as a propulsion fuel, 1945-1959|url=https://history.nasa.gov/SP-4404/ch8-11.htm|website=NASA History Program|publisher=National Aeronautics and Space Administration|accessdate=April 22, 2016}}</ref> The trailer was constructed by the Cambridge Corporation and had a capacity of 26,500 liters with a [[hydrogen]] loss rate of approximately 2 percent per day. The U-1 was a single [[axle]] [[semi-trailer]]. The specifications for its successor the U-2 a double axle semi-trailer were issued on 15 March 1957.
