{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}} {{Infobox Oil field | name = Ula | location_map = North Sea | location_map_width = | location_map_text = | coordinates_ref = | country = [[Norway]] | coordinates = {{coord|57|6|41.15|N|2|50|50.39|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | locblock = 7/12-2 | offonshore = Offshore | operator = [[AkerBP AS]] | partners = AkerBP AS (80%), [[Ørsted (company)|Dong Norge AS]] (20%) | image = | caption = | discovery = 1976 | startofproduction = 1986 | peakofproduction = | expectedabandonment = 2028 | oil_production_bbl/d = 10000 | est_oil_bbl = 18.1 | producingformations = Upper Jurassic<ref name=NPD>{{cite web|url=http://www.npd.no/engelsk/cwi/pbl/en/field/all/43800.htm |title=OLJEDIREKTORATET Norwegian Petroleum Directorate. Ula |publisher=Npd.no |date= |accessdate=24 April 2011}}</ref> }}
'''Ula''' ({{lang-no|Ulafeltet}}) is an offshore [[oil field]] located in the southern Norwegian section of [[North Sea]] along with [[Gyda oil field|Gyda]], [[Tambar oil field|Tambar]] and [[Tambar Øst|Tambar East]] fields making up the UGT area, usually attributed to [[DONG Energy]]'s main areas of exploration and production activity.<ref name=Rigzone> {{cite news | url= http://events.rigzone.com/news/article.asp?a_id=62524 | title= DONG Ups Stake in Norway's Ula Field | publisher=Rigzone | author= | date=2 June 2008 | accessdate=18 March 2010 }}</ref>
The Ula field was discovered in 1976 and came online in October 1986.<ref name="BP">{{cite web|url=http://www.akerbp.com/en/our-assets/production/ula/|title=AkerBP operated fields. Ula|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Akerbp.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref> It contains confirmed 69.98&nbsp;million m<sup>3</sup> of oil and 2.5&nbsp;million of [[Natural-gas processing#Contaminants in raw natural gas|NGL]].<ref name=NPD/>
==Ownership== AkerBP is the operator of the field with 80% of interest in the project. AkerBP's partner DONG Energy holds 20% of interest.<ref name=BP/> DONG Energy increased its initial share of 5% to 20% by acquiring [[Svenska Petroleum Exploration AB|Svenska Petroleum]]'s complete share of 15% for US$130&nbsp;million in 2008.<ref name=Rigzone/>
==Production== Ula is located in approximately {{convert|70|m|ft|abbr=on}} of water. The main reservoir stands at {{convert|3345|m|ft|abbr=on}} in the Upper Jurassic Ula Formation.<ref name=NPD/> The field has three conventional steel facilities with production, drilling, living quarters. It has 7 production and 2 water injection wells. Current production at Ula field is 10,000 bbl/d. The existing gas process plant was recently extended with a new module, turbine and compressor and has been operative since 2008. The gas from [[Blane oil field|Blane]] field is injected into the Ula reservoir for production. The gas produced at Ula field is re-injected into the field for increased recovery as well. The field is expected to be abandoned in 2028.<ref name=BP/> The produced oil is then transported by a pipeline to [[Ekofisk oil field]] and on to [[Teesside]] for refining.<ref name=NPD/> In 2009, [[Aker Solutions]] was awarded a contract to tieback Ula field to [[Oselvar oil field|Oselvar field]]. The work is expected to commence in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.subseaiq.com/data/PrintProject.aspx?project_id=433 |title=SubseaIQ Oselvar |publisher=Subseaiq.com |date= |accessdate=24 April 2011}}</ref> Once complete, the oil from DONG-operated Oselvar field which is {{convert|24|km|mi|}} from Ula will be pumped to facilities at Ula for processing.<ref> {{cite news | url= http://www.upstreamonline.com/live/article202196.ece | title= Aker Solutions ties up Ula job | newspaper=[[Upstream (newspaper)|Upstream Online]] | publisher=NHST Media Group | date=22 December 2009 | accessdate=18 March 2010 }}</ref>
